metadata.name: Diyalebuka #78
metadata.description:
Diyalebuka - "Thank you"! 

With this piece I hope to express my thanks and joy for being alive and able to create art. I hope the patterns and textures will bring you joy.

This piece is inspired by the patterns of the Ndebele of Southern Africa and the First Nations Salish of Vancouver Island.

* There are over 100 palettes arranged into 6 distinct families
* There can be between 2 and 10 bars

(The artwork will fit your available window and may take a while to generate if it's a larger resolution)

metadata.name: No-input Mixer #20
metadata.description:
No-input Mixer draws a canvas starting with an empty window, goes in to a feedback loop, then continues looping through alternating displacements.

Colors are divided into:

- Monochrome (50%)
- Red/Cyan (20%)
- Yellow/Blue (20%)
- Magenta/Green (10%)

Possibility of inverted output (30%)

Displacements are affected by hash. Other features include pixelation size, direction, separation and the amount of noisy area. 

"I think I find an equal relationship with no-input mixing board, which I didn't see with the guitar. When I played the guitar, "I" had to play the guitar. But with the mixing board, the machine would play me and the music would play the other two, and I would do something or maybe nothing."
- Toshimaru Nakamura

metadata.name: Terra #15
metadata.description:
The year is 2242. Humanity is desperate to find new habitable planets to escape a dying earth. To aid this process of space colonization, multiple drones have been released across galactic sectors on this large scale reconnaissance mission. This is a fragment of a larger speculative series investigating the concepts of space and time in the era of post-human condition.

This piece consists of five landscape types and six drone classes generated procedurally using noise and basic geometric shapes, driven by the seed to generate unique iterations.

Hit 's' to take a high-resolution(4096x4096) screenshot.

metadata.name: Neon Painter #12
metadata.description:
The Neon Painter / 2021

The Idea of Painter series got started when I received an artwork, oil painted canvas that my distant relative had painted and fell in love with it. From since I have been dreaming of a algorithm that generates similar art to canvas.

The Neon Painter is first step towards fulfilling my dream. This Painter was inspired by Chris Randall's work here at fxhash. Hopefully You will enjoy my Painters as much as I do enjoy making them.

Made with P5JS and neons.

metadata.name: linez #8
metadata.description:
graphical genart with a lot of features that determine the outcome.

the features are selected carefully and allow for rare combinations:
number of bars, palette, animation length, color mode, glitched (very rare), gradient smoothness,
noise elevation and scale, tiling incl. uv mode and "love handles" <3

the scene features full 3D and a simple orbit navigation allows you to discover it. left mouse click to rotate, right click to travel.

metadata.name: post boredom/ #55
metadata.description:
/i gave you nothing, you want more?
you'll get more nothing/

Post Boredom is a generative system that creates soft rippling and flowing gradients. The colour system is complex with RGB values varying depending on each other. It's unpredictable yet never unknown.

The name, Post Boredom, comes from the song by the band Every Time I Die. While I was working on this piece I noticed that the colour palette often looked similar to the album art of the bands newest album. titled Radical.

tw: @derek_morash, ig: gammastop

metadata.name: M-tore #17
metadata.description: This token generates abstract art using a recursive algorithm for rectangle splitting. The number of rectangles can be anywhere from 32 to 16384. There are several different strategies for splitting, each one producing distinctive results. The background can be dark or light. Color palettes are generated¬†programmatically¬†in eight different ways (e.g. monochromatic, complementary, analogous, etc.). Textures and effects are also generated programmatically using Perlin noise and pixel manipulation. To add dynamics, there is a probability of having some¬†uncertainty¬†in drawing rectangles, dots, and lines.

metadata.name: noiseD #7
metadata.description:
Noised - Series about the noise.

This one is all about the noise. Noise that flows through the canvas.
